text:
отношения с матерью (часть 4, заключение)

что до моей матери... ей было всё равно, я перестала её видеть в какой-то момент. меня приютила семья овчинниковой дарьи, её мама невероятной души человек, я никак не могу вспомнить их точный адрес! я бы очень хотела навестить эту женщину, что спасла меня буквально, в определённый момент.
последний раз я видела мать более четырёх лет назад. я не знаю люблю ли я этого человека, но увидев её я испытала весь спектр чувств от ненависти до желания спасти, защитить, пролечить, обогреть....
она не осталась в моей жизни надолго. я жила сама на птичьих правах у сожителя (дом мать продала сама, ещё до моего совершеннолетия, пока меня небыло в россии) с маленьким ребёнком на руках. несколько встреч, несколько тысяч рублей она выманила у меня на свои интересы обманным путём. я пыталась ей помочь, найти приют, работу, но она только злилась или высмеивала мои предложения, и вскоре снова исчезла оставив меня с огромным, невероятным, бездонным чувством вины и "новой" утраты.
с тех пор я не знаю о ней ничего.
но я хотела бы её найти и снова попытаться помочь.
честно сказать - я ненавижу себя. 
я должна была найти выход, я должна была помочь. на этом у меня всё.
спасибо.

#7днейвоспоминаний #янебоюсьсказать #мама #семейноефото #жизнь #подслушано #ненависть #любовь #селфхарм #metoo #mother #familyphotography #
name: Ирина Шост
tweet_full:
отношения с матерью (часть 4, заключение)

что до моей матери... ей было всё равно, я перестала её видеть в какой-то момент. меня приютила семья овчинниковой дарьи, её мама невероятной души человек, я никак не могу вспомнить их точный адрес! я бы очень хотела навестить эту женщину, что спасла меня буквально, в определённый момент.
последний раз я видела мать более четырёх лет назад. я не знаю люблю ли я этого человека, но увидев её я испытала весь спектр чувств от ненависти до желания спасти, защитить, пролечить, обогреть....
она не осталась в моей жизни надолго. я жила сама на птичьих правах у сожителя (дом мать продала сама, ещё до моего совершеннолетия, пока меня небыло в россии) с маленьким ребёнком на руках. несколько встреч, несколько тысяч рублей она выманила у меня на свои интересы обманным путём. я пыталась ей помочь, найти приют, работу, но она только злилась или высмеивала мои предложения, и вскоре снова исчезла оставив меня с огромным, невероятным, бездонным чувством вины и "новой" утраты.
с тех пор я не знаю о ней ничего.
но я хотела бы её найти и снова попытаться помочь.
честно сказать - я ненавижу себя. 
я должна была найти выход, я должна была помочь. на этом у меня всё.
спасибо.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
today is a big day is the woo-woo world, 11-11. 
it’s a way to really create the world we want to live in. 
this isn’t some fluffy say your intentions and affirmations and wait for the phone to ring kind of day.  it’s a day to write down how you want to feel in 6 months, and then ask 
what do you need to do
who do you need to be
and then go make that happen

you offer a voice that no one else has 
you offer a friendship that no one else can offer
you have a unique, god given talent that no one else has

and if you haven’t figured out what that is yet- let’s do it together.

text:
une fois n'est pas coutume, je copie ci-desous le texte qui accompagne initialement le dessin sur mon blog. 
to see the english version of the drawings, swipe left!
traduction du texte des dessins: @laurie_nce 
peut-être trouveras-tu, ami lecteur, que c'est une curieuse façon de rendre hommage à l'angleterre. c'est vrai que les tenues des anglais et des anglaises sont parfois quelque peu approximatives. mais cet affranchissement des règles vestimentaires (et capillaires!) est symptomatique de la liberté que les britanniques ont de pouvoir se balader comme bon leur semble, sans contrainte ou presque. alors oui, c'est habillée "à l'anglaise" que je veux leur rendre hommage. un hommage aux anglais pour la paix royale qu'ils foutent aux femmes et aux anglaises pour la façon à la fois extravagante et naturelle avec laquelle elle s'empare de cette liberté.
car, redevenons sérieux une minute. il s'agit bien d'une liberté, fondamentale, mais bien trop méconnue dans nos contrées françaises. sur le papier, nous avons les mêmes libertés que les anglaises, notamment celle d'aller et venir quand bon nous semble et dans la tenue qui nous chante. la réalité est un peu moins rose.

text:
woody allen, el (in)genio incomprendido.
...
probablemente sea el cineasta vivo más odiado del mundo. todo el rencor que se le guarda, es solo comparable a la admiración que, por otro lado, sus seguidores le profesan.

a principios de año, durante la campaña de promoción de ‘wonder wheel’, woody  comparó la vida con un parque de atracciones, en el que la mitad de los tiovivos no funciona y la otra mitad procura emociones mucho menos intensas de lo que uno esperaba. 
pocos lo saben, pero su hijo, ronan farrow, fue quién destapó el caso weinstein. lo hizo un poco a modo de venganza, para acabar con el hombre que había salvado a su padre cuando hollywood le dio la espalda. el movimiento que su reportaje desencadenó dio fuerza a su hermana, para retomar la denuncia a los supuestos “abusos” de su progenitor, desestimados en el pasado por falta de pruebas, ahora apoyados, y casi se podría decir corroborados, por una multitud anónima que sintió compasión por el testimonio de dylan farrow.

actualmente, woody allen tiene una película hecha que amazon se niega a distribuir. sus actores le dieron la espalda, así como hollywood. solo alec baldwin y diane keaton han salido en su defensa. .

cuando se estrenó ‘wonder wheel’ acababa de estallar el caso weinstein y comenzaba a salpicarle el #metoo. su publicista prohibió a la prensa preguntar por la polémica. woody habló de su película, pero también de su biografía y pensamientos.
en una de sus últimas entrevistas, el genio dijo que lo único que diferenciaba la vida del parque de atracciones de coney island, era que esta solía ser “tan fea por fuera” como lo era por dentro.

got stress? #metoo
:
#acute stress is necessary. life saving, even. in a serious situation, our body dumps the hormone cortisol and we fight or flight. after the event, we metabolize the cortisol and get back to living... :
:
our "modern" lifestyle creates #chronic stress though. chronic stress = a steady supply of excess cortisol, which is connected to:
✔ chronic fatigue...
✔ insomnia...
✔ migraines...
✔ increased blood sugar...
✔ acid reflux...
✔ hostility...
✔ belly fat storage...
✔ inflammation and arthritis...
✔ lowered immune response...
✔ decreased metabolism...
:
1) what's something (someone?) you can remove from your life or schedule that will reduce your stress?
:
2) is there an area in your home that you could #declutter or beautify to make a small stress-free oasis?
:
3) what's something healthy you can add in to your life and routine in order to reduce stress?...
:

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

name: Proud Liddle Me Too Pounder™
tweet_full:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

the guardian

@jakartapac is back on stage with #blackbird , a powerful one-act play by david harrower. it tells the story of a woman confronting a man from her past, as they deal with trauma, heartbreak, and attachment. 
this play is performed as a part of the 16 film festival. with it, we hope to start a dialogue about sexual violence against women and children, and how to become a better support system for its survivors. the proceeds from this play will be donated to yayasan pulih.

you can be a part of this force of change with us!

support this play and donate now. any amount will do:
rp75k - afford us 1 hour of rehearsal time
225k - 1 day of rehearsal 
500k - 1 week of  transport and logistics
1mio - 2 weeks of water and food for cast and crews 
3mio - licensing fee to stage this play
5mio - lighting/set development

donate now by transfer to mandiri, acc. no. 1290011184773, yayasan jakarta performing arts center 
confirm your donation by sending the transfer receipt by email or whatsapp to alex (puti.rahmasari@gmail.com/ +628170770380) or
andi (personalproemail@gmail.com/ +6281314468264)

all donors will be acknowledged in the program book. donation of idr1.000k and up also will be mentioned during dialogue session and workshop. thank you!

text:
de bullshit over de seksualiteit van de vrouw.

mijn creatiekracht ligt op dezelfde plek als mijn seksualiteit. zo groeit als ik creëer ook het verlangen om op mijn eigen manier sensueel te zijn. 
mijn seksualiteit. dus niet van jou!
dat is de eerste die naar boven komt. boosheid ofzo. alsof ik, als ik in contact ben met mijn seksualiteit opeens open ben voor bussiness en jij je daar toe mag bedienen. dan moet ik mij er ook nog voor schamen dat ik deze gevoelens bij je oproep als ik nee zeg. 1 ontmoeting waarin je ontdekt hoe machteloos je bent tegen mannelijke seksuele agressie is genoeg. ik ben jaren bang geweest voor mannen, mijn eigen seksualiteit en creatiekracht.

een laag dieper ontdek ik dat ik als vrouw natuurlijk ook verlang naar mannelijke energie. dus ja, mijn seksualiteit betekent ook dat ik jou aantrekkelijk kan vinden. het kan ook betekenen dat ik jou wil en wil dat jij naar mij verlangt. 
want man van nu, wat ben je mooi!
ik zie heel veel mooie, intelligente, warme, moedige, krachtige mannen om me heen.

ik snap dat je soms niet meer weet wat vrouwen van je willen. we lopen vaak ergens vast tussen angst, overmoedigheid, overschreeuwen en verstoppen. onpeilbaar. tijd dat we gewoon open zijn.  ik kan alleen voor mezelf spreken. 
ik draag mijn kleding en mijn lijf voor mij en mijn eigen gevoel van sensualiteit.

de man die ik het aantrekkelijkst vind, is de man die me laat merken dat hij me ziet. en dan zijn eigen controle kan houden. 'ik wil je en als je mij wil ben ik hier. ik vind je leuk en wil wel moeite doen maar dat vraagt ook dat jij een opening tot contact geeft.' zelf heb ik gekozen om mezelf met 1 man te delen. alleen zijn seksuele verlangens wil ik beantwoorden. het voelt ook goed dat het meest heilige deel van mezelf maar voor 1 man is. niet omdat het moet maar omdat ik dat kies. 
dat betekent niet dat ik je niet af en toe kan bevestigen dat ik jou ook zie en mooi vind. 
staan voor wat ik kies vraagt zelfcontrole als jij langs loopt of voor me staat met je fijne energie. toch is mijn man het waard.

ben jij je bewust van je eigen seksualiteit? durf jij daar open over te zijn naar jezelf zodat je toegang hebt tot je eigen creatiekracht?
name: Jouw universum, Margot Peters

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this picture is about an incident that happened on october 23.
.

on october 23, tamil nadu woke up to something that should've stunned it to shame. there is a village called thalavaipatti,which is located 14 kms away from the outskirts of salem near aathur. a 13 year old (8th grade) girl named rajalakshmi was beheaded by her neighbour dhinesh kumar the previous evening. she had allegedly spurned his advances. this happended when the #metoo campaigns were going viral,and yet nobody seemed to notice such incident.what happened was,she was sexually harassed by him previously.she even told this to her parents but they couldn't do anything as they were from a dalit family and he was from a dominant caste.that day,when chinnaponnu (rajalakshmi's mother) and rajalakshmi were stringing flowers,he came there with a sickle and beheaded her inspite of chinnaponnu's intervention.then he headed home with rajalakshmi's head where his wife sarada advised him to discard it elsewhere.subsequently, they went to police station together and surrendered.sarada convinced the police that he was mentally ill but it was just a ploy to save her husband.during investigation police made it clear that he was mentally and physically sound.they police see's this as a caste crime whereas the society see's this as a sex crime.in my opinion it's both,because he sexually assaulted her first and then he was enraged that a dalit woman had the audacity to spurn him.now he can be out on bail, which shouldn't be happening.in my opinion the case should be tried under posco act(death penalty).its a shame that we all failed to notice such a horrible incident.rape is a serious crime,i feel that the convicted rapist should experience consequences in keeping with the severity of their crime,not based on the privilege of their caste or the colour of their skin.women in india have always been worshipped as goddess and all the rapes, acid attacks and everything,all these has put us in shame.something has to be done to put an end to this cruelty.i hereby conclude that if we all join our hands together we might be able to put an end to this. #justiceforrajalakshmi 
@prila_art .
.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
men’s studies: le blog des hommes et des masculinités
christoph may – fondateur de men’s studies
les témoins d’outre-mer, francetv "we all win, if men start to questioning themselves „hey, my name is christoph may. two years ago i started a blog on men and masculinity studies. i question manhood in a hypercritical way.

for example i ask for extreme masculinities in online culture wars or i write about the representation of tough guys like the men of steel, kylo ren or spiderman. what about the nerdy sexism in the big bang theory? why there is no #metoo-debate in hip-hip and rap? or why are more than 80 percent of all games in the gaming industry still running in combat-mode? questions like that. you know, it’s everywhere!

so i also wanna talk to the people, especially men. i do lectures on hatespeech and misogyny and i offer workhops for startups and business guys where you learn to kill your male privileges or how to question your male fantasies about flying to the mars, selfdriving cars or virtual reality porn.

and my experience shows, that all kind of men are really interested in that. they wanna get rid of their mansplaining-behaviour, they wanna be emotional daddies and take responsibility for their kids and best of all: they wanna support women and womens rights.

i think, a lot of men understood, that we all win, if men start to questioning themselves. so we just need to push that forward!

i wanna accallerate the crisis of men, cause i see it as a chance to give up power, to change your male view and finally to be a better man: positive, selfcritical and feminist.“ statement by #christophmay

#gender #genderstudies #feminist #feminism #männlichkeitsforschung #mensstudies #männerforschung #maleprivilege #männlichkeit #masculinity #masculinitystudies #toxicmasculinity

text:
men’s studies: le blog des hommes et des masculinités
christoph may – fondateur de men’s studies
les témoins d’outre-mer, francetv "we all win, if men start to questioning themselves „hey, my name is christoph may. two years ago i started a blog on men and masculinity studies. i question manhood in a hypercritical way.

for example i ask for extreme masculinities in online culture wars or i write about the representation of tough guys like the men of steel, kylo ren or spiderman. what about the nerdy sexism in the big bang theory? why there is no #metoo-debate in hip-hip and rap? or why are more than 80 percent of all games in the gaming industry still running in combat-mode? questions like that. you know, it’s everywhere!

so i also wanna talk to the people, especially men. i do lectures on hatespeech and misogyny and i offer workhops for startups and business guys where you learn to kill your male privileges or how to question your male fantasies about flying to the mars, selfdriving cars or virtual reality porn.

and my experience shows, that all kind of men are really interested in that. they wanna get rid of their mansplaining-behaviour, they wanna be emotional daddies and take responsibility for their kids and best of all: they wanna support women and womens rights.

i think, a lot of men understood, that we all win, if men start to questioning themselves. so we just need to push that forward!

i wanna accallerate the crisis of men, cause i see it as a chance to give up power, to change your male view and finally to be a better man: positive, selfcritical and feminist.“ statement by #christophmay

text_retweet:
regram from @feministerna -  våld mot kvinnor är en global pandemi 
25 november är ett viktigt datum för alla feministiska organisationer runt om i världen för då är det den internationella dagen mot våld mot kvinnor. på årsdagen av den första svenska hashtagen i #metoo, 8 november inrättade vi en minnesdag för patriarkatets offer och vi i f! dedikerar dagarna fram till 25/11 mot våldet. ✏️ skriv under vårt upprop!
https://med.feministisktinitiativ.se/ga-langre-metoo

frihet från våld är en mänsklig rättighet
mäns våld mot kvinnor är ett gigantiskt folkhälso- och säkerhetsproblem, en global pandemi enligt who, var tredje kvinna i världen utsätts någon gång för allvarligt fysiskt eller sexuellt våld från en man. den senaste svenska jämställdhetsutredningen konstaterar att resurstilldelningen inte motsvarar problemets omfattning och allvarlighetsgrad.

frihet från våld är en grundläggande mänsklig rättighet. #metoo har lyft på locket till en tryckkokare fylld av uppdämd sorg, vanmakt och ilska. nu är vi med och omvandlar den kraften till konkret handling. tillsammans kan vi sätta stopp för mäns våld mot kvinnor nu. ✏️ skriv under vårt upprop!

text:
this is the end of bâtard festival amsterdam 2018 >>>
today is day 50 of the 100 day house #2 ! >>>
this means we arrived in between, in the middle of our program, again fully in light, and we can only look back to celebrate; and we can only look in front of to build-up the path towards the last 50 days before the darkness 🌌🌌🌌
today program starts from 15:30 (doors open at 15:00, feel welcome to arrive on time!):
— words for the future | completed series launch by @nienkescholts
— wanderings of a flaming body by sara hamadeh (dutch premiere)
— what is the new festival | public talk by lara staal & other guest curators
— launch newspaper #2 | day 50
tickets for day 5 via >>> https://bit.ly/2czvkp1
.

text: anyone interested in joining a women’s group in the new year, there will be fun, educational workshops all themed around female empowerment. each session will have a theme and consist of a talk,demo or workshop followed by time out to enjoy a brew and a chat with other women in a male and child free environment. this is not a man hating group it’s more about realising women are equal. will be based in the rotherham area. let me know if interested and i’ll keep you updated #womenempowerment #wisewomen #familylife #metime #metoo #kidfree #womenonly

ann-mari leinonen: sentillä rakkautta - liattu

text:
in light of the current court case involving #geoffreyrush and the comments made on the recent episode of @abctv #qanda by neil armfield about theatre involving a ‘sexual energy that actors use to connect with the audience and the cast’, we wanted to share part of our interview with actress matilda ridgway @tillyridgway from last year in which she speaks about these topics. no person, in any workplace, should be made to feel unsafe or unsupported when reporting inappropriate behaviour. no person should have to put up with sexual harassment for the sake of conserving a sense of ‘playfulness’ or ‘sexual energy’. it’s the perpetrator who ruins that safe space, not the victim. 
watch the full interview via the link in our profile. ✊

text:
детские рюкзачки metoo собачки🐩 - маленькие модницы оценят их по достоинству. они мягкие и очень простые в использовании.

удобный и прочный рюкзачок будет одним из первых аксессуаров для юных леди.🏵 некоторые модели для безопасности оснащены снимаемым поводком. основное отделение закрывается молнией, лямки регулируются.

высота: 27 см
ширина: 24 см
материал: высококачественный мягкий плюш, трикотаж
можно стирать в стиральной машинке на деликатном режиме.

text:
내용을 모른 채로 가 머리속과 세포 사이사이 고인 찌뿌두둥한 무언가를 마구 쏟아내 버렸다. 앞으로 닥칠수 있을 일들, 누군가가 뒤에서 나에 대해 그렇게 말할까봐 무섭고 두려운 말들, 듣고 싶었던 격려와 응원이 작품속 꽉 차있었다. 줄줄 흐르는 눈물을 막아내기에 의식은 턱없이 힘이 부족했다. 
완전한 불면의 밤은 꽤 줄었지만 사실 2월 구정 이후 상쾌한 꿀잠은 손에 꼽을 정도다. 거의 어렴풋한 풋잠으로 아침을 맞다 보니 아토피의 재발, 하릴없이 예민해지는 신경, 집중력과 자존의 저하, 의식적인 불안과 두려움에 여전히 종종 사로잡히곤 하는 것이다. 정말 일이 많아 곯아 떨어질만한 날도.
그 밤들과 낮 사이 꾸물꾸물 들어찬 물질들이 피부와 세포 사이, 뇌물질 사이에 들어차 있었음을 오늘 깜짝 놀라며 체감했다. 동시에 해소 또한.
방혜영 연출님, 고맙습니다. 정말 정말 고맙습니다. 큰 응원과 해소가 되었어요. 배우분들께도요. 제대로 인사 못 드리고 와 죄송해요. 
오늘 막공인데 내년에도 또 또 또 많이 많이 오르길 마음으로 바랍니다. 감사합니다🙏

#우리집에손주며느릿감이온다 #극단공외 #작품연기다훌륭합니다 #방혜영작가연출 #경험과상상 #metoo #withyou #위안부 #여성들에게힘이되는연극 #주변인들이2차피해를하지않을수있는 #관심을거두지말아주세요 #잊지말아주세요 #아직한참더가야합니다 #힘이되어주세요 #함께가주세요 #함께말해요
name: 오민정

text:
i can't believe it's been exactly a year since i had that massive shift in energy and finally for the first time in my life felt internal peace. to finally realise the one thing that was holding me back was i didn't know who i was without all the trauma and baggage, and i then had to make the decision to unlearn everything and pretty much start again. its been one hell of a journey this year, and definitely had my fair share of challenges which i keep working my way through. happiness is everything to me, and i am trying my hardest to give life it all, and give my daughter everything she needs. i have definitely lost friends along the way but i'd much rather have very few close friends than surrounded by toxic people that thrive off dragging everyone down with their drama and negative energy. keep thriving forward is the way. i have learned many lessons on this journey, and i'm excited to see where it leads.
🌈🦄🧘‍♀️🤸‍♀️👩‍👧❤️🧡💛💚💙💜👣🌄🌅🚗

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
🍬🍬🍬
saquemos los traumas y las piedras, que la culpa la paguen los culpables...
hicimos ruido y estamos todas vivas...
tuve que leer muchas historias para poder contar la mía...
"chicas, hagan este ejercicio por favor, yo lo estoy empezando a hacer. no pongan más "llegue bien" pon: "estoy viva". porque lo que estamos avisando cuando decimos llegué bien, es que nadie nos violó, es que no estamos en una bolsa de consorcio, estás diciendo que estás viva, no que llegaste a casa. prueba no llamar a tú amiga que llegaste, y contar las veces que te llama por teléfono " fragmento de la grandiosa zuleika esnal del 9no encuentro maría cher mujeres que inspiran.
yo también he tenido miedo... tambien me han seguido, parado por la calle, me han insultado y faltado el respeto por ir bien vestida. me han acosado una noche de fiesta por no querer nada y me han acosado durante meses un cliente del lugar dónde hice las prácticas con 18 años... me han mandado mensajes ofreciéndome dinero por servicios que no ofrezco, también se han intentado pasar de listos conmigo. 
creo que todas tenemos por desgracia mucho que contar y callamos porqué tenemos tristemente interiorizado que tenemos que hacerlo porque vivimos en un patriarcado de mierda, y aún es más triste decir que yo he tenido mucha suerte. ¡porque yo sigo viva!, hay muchas que no, hay muchas que han tenido mucha peor suerte y la peor de ellas. por eso hoy tocaba este grito de #respect me apetecía y para que no se nos olvide nunca simplemente.. porque #metoo 
yo estoy acá!. 💪❤️

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i will not accept what i cannot change. i will change what i cannot accept. 
i am here today, standing up for our children, for our sisters and brothers, for all victims of sexual assault, for myself. i came in protest of the judicial ruling of a man who’s name is protected by the court. after being found guilty of sexually assaulting two teenage girls on separate occasions, the “appropriate” sentence was determined to be two weeks of jail time. one of his victims was hospitalized and left in critical condition. her physical rehabilitation took far longer than the time he will serve, let alone the emotional recovery that will last a lifetime. my heart is broken. i cannot believe this happened in my community. i cannot believe how much our judicial system has failed to protect our youth and failed to support survivors of sexual assault. 
if you share my opinion: that the judicial system should not allow people with a clear bias in favor of violent offenders to determine our fates, please sign the petition to have judge paul meyers removed from his position. i have posted the link in my bio. i encourage you to do your own research into judge meyer’s career and rulings. i ask that you please do not sign the petition based off my account alone. i do not believe in asserting power over someone’s life in a way that could negatively affect their future without merit. 
thank you for taking the time to read this. thank you to all the people who spoke so bravely today, to everyone who came out in support, and to everyone who voices support for survivors. 
#metoo #timesup

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
//me too//.
.
.
.
 just the other day, scrolling through instagram, i chanced by a statement which really got me thinking about how narrow minded we as a society have grown up. while we are constantly cribbing about issues that are important to us, we are assigning a back seat to the broader picture, which potentially is more dangerous should we ever reach a level of that acute a crisis. "#metoo - said mother earth"
this statement, upon perception presents a picture of gut wrenching pathos that we've brought upon ourselves, either by wronging our home planet or maintaining an unappreciative silence instead of speaking up against them. what use is your voice of, if you don't use it against injustice? 
what we are doing is calling the attack with a spade as gardening; when what we need to do is stand up..not because it's the air that you, as an individual breathe is unclean but because in doing so, you stand up for all those that survive on unclean air and water for their entire lifetime, the number of whom, according to world statistics today is a surprising 2.5 billion ( approximately 35 percent). trees, a whooping 50% of which has been cut down by brutal inventions in the last century, literally are the source of the very thing we survive on. would you call the axeman cutting the branch he's sitting on wise? and yet humans are the most intelligent among creatures to ever exist. oh, the irony.
the society has taken a collective step back and we did nothing. strangely enough, that's where the crux of the issue lies.
this hour calls for us to stop being so self conscious and quit merely feeling sorrow. action is so much more powerful  than silent resentment, let's take each opportunity to prove so. let's stand up, united by the vision of a better tomorrow.
.
.
.
writer- rimli das

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
i'm so proud of my sister @thatyalda for organizing with me against rape culture in our community. standing in solidarity with survivors & denouncing patriarchy and rape culture alongside hundreds of people today felt so meaningful. seeing so many young women shouting "don't fucking touch me" was so empowering. watching as people mobilized to defend and support each other moved me. all the beautiful signs were raised high over and over, and i hope that survivors were afforded a space to be recognized for their strengths, not their victimhood.
no justice, no peace! ✊🏽#metoo

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

pamela anderson says #metoo movement “paralyzes men:” "my mother taught me don't go into a hotel with a stranger” -  blogged by: @raquelharristv (@60minutes)

ex-playmate #pamelaanderson is under fire after making controversial remarks about the #metoo movement. anderson discussed her thoughts on feminism during a “60 minutes australia” interview. while referring to her time modeling for “playboy,” she mentioned how comfortable she was about her actions. "i think ("playboy") was very empowering and no one forced me to do anything," she said. "i think this feminism can go too far – i'm a feminist but i think that this third wave feminism is a bore, i think it paralyzes men i think that this me too movement is a bit too much for me. i'm sorry; i'll probably get killed for saying that."when asked about #harveryweinstein she highlighted specific lessons her mother taught her. "my mother taught me don't go into a hotel with a stranger, and if someone answers the door in a bathrobe and it's supposed to be a business meeting, maybe i should go with somebody else," she said. "you're talking about harvey weinstein?" the interviewer asked her. "yeah, i think that some things are just common sense. or if you go, in get the job," she said, laughing. "i'm canadian i'm going to speak my mind okay? i'm sorry, i'm sorry, i'm not politically correct, maybe." while her take may be somewhat opposite of the feminist movement, anderson has spoken out about issues that matter to women like the dangers of ridesharing apps and pornography. --------------------------------------------------#therealremyredd #blackmedia #bothervex  #blackinamerica  #blacklivesmatter  #blackhistoryiseveryday #blackhistory  #blackhistorymonth #stephcurry #lebron #nas #beyonce #beyoncé #kimkardashian #cardib  #nickiminaj  #worldstar #getthestrap #colinkaepernick #hiphop #nike #boycottnfl #cosby #billcosby #danielclary

"i think ("playboy") was very empowering and no one forced me to do anything," she said. "i think this feminism can go too far – i am a feminist but i think that this third wave feminism is a bore, i think it paralyzes men i think that this me too movement is a bit too much for me. i am sorry; i'll probably get killed for saying that."when asked about #harveryweinstein she highlighted specific lessons her mother taught her. "my mother taught me do not go into a hotel with a stranger, and if someone answers the door in a bathrobe and it is supposed to be a business meeting, maybe i should go with somebody else," she said. "you are talking about harvey weinstein?" the interviewer asked her. "yeah, i think that some things are just common sense. or if you go, in get the job," she said, laughing. "i am canadian i am going to speak my mind okay? i am sorry, i am sorry, i am not politically correct, maybe." while her take may be somewhat opposite of the feminist movement, anderson has spoken out about issues that matter to women like the dangers of ridesharing apps and pornography. --------------------------------------------------#therealremyredd #blackmedia #bothervex  #blackinamerica  #blacklivesmatter  #blackhistoryiseveryday #blackhistory  #blackhistorymonth #stephcurry #lebron #nas #beyonce #beyoncé #kimkardashian #cardib  #nickiminaj  #worldstar #getthestrap #colinkaepernick #hiphop #nike #boycottnfl #cosby #billcosby #danielclary

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
12 mujeres mueren a diario en américa latina😩🤷 pese a la adopción de una batería de leyes pioneras, la violencia contra las mujeres persiste en la región debido a la impunidad y a un clima de permisividad social. de los 25 países del mundo con las tasas más altas de feminicidio, 14 están en la región latinoamericana.
😩😩 doce mujeres mueren asesinadas a diario en américa latina. pese a la adopción de una batería de leyes pioneras, la violencia contra las mujeres persiste en la región debido a la impunidad y a un clima de permisividad social, estiman responsables y expertos.♨️
••• "hemos tenido importantes avances en normativa, pero a pesar de eso la tasa de femicidios sigue siendo alta", se lamenta ana aminta madrid, ministra del instituto nacional de la mujer de honduras, uno de los países de la región con el mayor número de feminicidios (466 en 2016, según cifras de la cepal), en un encuentro sobre la violencia de género en parís.
••• en los últimos años hubo avances significativos en la región, con la aprobación en 18 países -entre ellos argentina, brasil, colombia y ecuador- de leyes o reformas a los códigos penales, en que se tipifica el delito de asesinato de una mujer por el solo hecho de ser mujer, bajo la denominación de femicidio o feminicidio🕯️
••• fue también en américa latina, más precisamente en argentina, donde surgió el movimiento ni una menos, por la igualdad de género, contra el patriarcado y los femicidios, que tuvo impacto mundial, y la primavera violeta, un movimiento de despertar social que nació en méxico contra la violencia machista.⚙️ pero a pesar de esto, el panorama en la región es desolador: de los 25 países del mundo con las tasas más altas de feminicidio, 14 están en américa latina y el caribe.📍
•••
entre los casos más escalofriantes destaca el reciente asesinato en perú de eyvi ágreda, que fue rociada con gasolina y quemada en un bus por un excolega que la acosaba por un amor no correspondido. la joven de 22 años murió en un hospital por quemaduras en más del 60% del cuerpo.🔎

text: this last month i checked into a rehab facility for alcohol addiction. i’ve struggled many years with abusing alcohol to escape many traumatic situations, until it became necessary for me to function. i’ve showed up to work, church, meetings, parties, conferences etc under the influence. i never imagined this being my reality. being a christian and a youth leader, i was ashamed, embarrassed, guilty, frustrated, afraid of what people would think, and who i would disappoint.  little did i know that leaving what i knew as “normal” would be the best decision i’ve ever made. i would have died if i didn’t decide to go. it was the best and worst weeks of my life. addressing my addiction head on has been the hardest thing i’ve ever done. however, i have never been at more peace, i have never loved myself more, and i have never been in more control of my life than i am now. i met so many people who have now become my life long friends! if you’re like me and battle the disease of addiction of any kind, i just want you to know #metoo. it’s okay to be exactly where you’re at. i just want you to know, i’m here for you, and i would love to walk through this with you. i’m not perfect, i still have a long road ahead of me but damn being sober 30 days feels amazing! i’m taking my life back 24 hours at a time! to those who have loved me through the worst parts of my addiction, thank you! to those who have loved and walked with me everyday up until now, thank you! here’s to another 30 days! #30dayssober #livingmybestlife #icanandiwill #onedayatatime #soberlife #recovery #jer2911 #metoo #addiction #staythecourse #godstrong #icandoallthings #godstilllovesme #takingmylifeback

#metoo :
it was the year 2012. i used to go to the market in the city of khandwa, where i, then stayed, always with my parents. one evening, when i was walking through the main road, an aged guy, much aged like he must have been in his late 50s or early 60s.  he was actually walking behind us for a long time. suddenly he walked past me, touched me behind and my arms as well.  it all happened like in a second's time,  but my reflex worked. i ran behind him, and even he started running. mom dad were infront of me so they couldn't see this all. but when i ran, dad and everyone around understood what could have happened. they caught the man.  and, to my relief, i slapped him twice. he exactly has spoken these words : "usne chote kapde pehena tha isiliye mujhe chadh gayi thi". and i was only wearing a knee length dress. this incident frightened me but also brought me a courage that if i fight against the wrong, they will have to weaken in their knees. like this song i played, "despacito" , i was growing to learn defending myself "slowly". ❤
.

text:
2) one night stand
•
she’s having fun with her friends at a bar. she smiles at a man from across the room, and he smiles back. he buys her a drink, she’s flattered. she’s now a target. they have small talk and she decides to leave with him. as they approach his house her body becomes numb. the rest is a blur. like many, it’s extremely difficult for her to come to terms with the fact that she is now a victim. like many, she is afraid to tell someone.
•
she blames herself... but in the end, she has the courage to say out loud that this is not okay and a newfound bravery to be able to say, “me too.”
•

she’s having fun with her friends at a bar. she smiles at a man from across the room, and he smiles back. he buys her a drink, she’s flattered. she’s now a target. they have small talk and she decides to leave with him. as they approach his house her body becomes numb. the rest is a blur. like many, it’s extremely difficult for her to come to terms with the fact that she is now a victim. like many, she is afraid to tell someone.

text:
my life has never been easy. i’ve been through a lot, but everyone has. i’ve been on journey to grow & heal from my childhood for the last 2 years, before that i was a mess; sad, insecure and downright mean most of the time and sometimes i still am. i build walls with most people because that’s all i’ve ever been able to do to protect myself. i’ve learned over the last few years that i’m way too hard on myself & set unrealistic expectations for myself, when i don’t achieve them i beat myself up for hours, days and even weeks. i over analyze and over think literally e.v.e.r.y.t.h.i.n.g. i want to be healthy; mind, body & soul but i’m still a work in progress. i was mentally & sexually abused most of my childhood and almost all the people in my life including my immediate family don’t even know because i’ve always been too ashamed to say the words out loud, but i’ve come to realize this is not my shame i am carrying around. i don’t want pitty or sympathy i just want people to realize not everything is as it seems. i’m still a work in progress but at least i’m trying, and i’m proud of that. 
#thecouragetoheal #workinprogess #selflove #metoo

text:
teacher and tattoo. ⁣
⁣
i have been told over and over again that these are two things that do not belong together.⁣
⁣
this tattoo is one of my most meaningful tattoos. i say this because it breaks stereotypes on so many different levels. people are so quick to judge tattoo artists and the people who get tattoos. ⁣
⁣
i am a teacher and i have tattoos. ⁣
⁣
the man who gave me this tattoo has a beautiful family and i am lucky enough to have his daughter in my class. this is a perfect example that people that give/have tattoos are not automatically rebellious, unable to get a job, uneducated, mean, irrisponsible, wild, bad parents, and the list can go on forever. ⁣
⁣
i have tattoos and i am a teacher. i have tattoos and i am kind. i have tattoos and i am intelligent. i have tattoos and i value helping others. i have tattoos and it does not give you the right to question my worth or capabilities as an educator and/or human!!!!!!!

text:
what is trauma? how does it develop? how does it affect the survivors and how can they heal?

this book will answer the questions. it's based on #vanderkolk's 30 years clinical works as a psychiatrist. i must say up front, this book is a masterpiece.

trauma isn't only experienced by the survivor of war or disaster, most of the cases are based on domestic violence and sexual abuse esp in childhood.

remember how you can't forget swimming or riding a bicycle? it's because humans have muscle memory and it happens in trauma. it shuts down the higher brain which regulates self awareness. that's why the survivors may feel immobilization (inescapable shock) and dissociation.

the conscious mind forget the details as a part of defense mechanism, but unconsciously the experience still lingers deep. people with trauma fail integrate the experience as the past. they're frozen in time. their bodies stuck within the constant state of tension and alert which may cause emotional sensitivity and health problems.

also it's possible for the survivors to not remember anything (since the trauma is repressed) until something triggers them! even though they don't remember well, they may feel uncomfortable in their own skin, not connected with anyone, or not belong in the world. they forget the details, but not the sensation. this is what we call as #ptsd.

to heal trauma we need to continue the narrative, cut the loop, and create a closure. kolk's proposed emdr therapy & neurofeedback to help the survivors remember. yes, no matter how scary, we must revisit the memory!

afterwards, we can continue with body work: yoga, theatre, dance, anything that makes us in tune with our own body! small thing like fixing our posture matters too. when we're in harmony with our body, we're in harmony with the world.

for more details you can read the excerpt above because there's a huuge amount of knowledge that i got from this book 😊 kork's idea to teach emotional awareness for children (last pic) is also brilliant! definitely a must read for all psychologists, healers, and survivors out there.

text: today marks 366 days of recovery since one of the most traumatic events of my life. my self-worth and trust in others was lost, and i woke up almost every night paralyzed for quite some time. despite my trauma i am here one year later, surviving and living my life the best i can. i still have my bad days... i won't get into details on those too much because this post isn't about that. this is about recognizing that i am actively working toward recovery and even though i have had set backs along the way i am so proud of myself for how far i've come. in the past year i have done some serious self reflection and have learned to own my identity. i intend to continue to do that more day by day, in order to become the best version of me possible! here's to recovery. ❤️ #metoo #recoveryisnotlinear

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
i'm just reading about the exotism of black men from slavery to modern america, first on the plantation - modern day porn. oddly, there is no real discussion about the paradigm that underscored this wicked history: white fragility, male and female
.

and first up, documented narratives of the sexual and gender diversity *among* slaves, for both men and woman, remain all but invisible; some slaves had warped (stockholm sydrome-esk) sexual affairs, love stories, etc., with their masters ...like frederick douglass (-- i know; it's fucking true. take the moment you need). the larger point is slaves were gay, trans, etc.,; sexual diversity isnt new, but you have to dig for these stories bc the (very accurate) overarching narrative was hypersexualization of slaves... but, um, where is the part about timid white girls feining a disingenuous "fear" of the black body (both male and female) to stimulate their purity in the eyes of their protector ...the proverbial master
.

it's missing leads like this that actually hold white female *humanity* back (i actually wrote about this shit in my book and it's effect on homogeneous notions of american femininity, which are basically "act like a confused child forever). i mean, it's actually white girls who have suffered the most from the absence of this narrative -- i know this shit, it's hillary clinton types who dont
.

and if we dare to unpack this (totally inauthentic) "fear" we would find a strange hybridization of fetishism, envy and posturing (a creepy as fuck) power dynamic, which is basically the makings of the *institution* of misogyny, which is then further fractioned by preformative gender ideals: the docile female plays dead before the heroic man, bc racism is just *one* of the elements that trigger the practice of the *binary construction of misogyny*, and lynching takes place
.

and all this white fragility *began* with frigidity as a signifier for class status, which is a fascinating isolated history in itself, which i could spin off on for months
.

now, i *realize* nobody else talked about this at the dinner table but my dad to my uncle's with me just around, but white girls! learn *your* fucking *history*

text:
is your lover gentle, present, and kind?

if you’ve had any that weren’t or have experienced any kind of abuse, unkindness, or sex without love, it can hinder the flow of your life force or shakti energy both in your body and in your relations.

if you don’t have total safety and trust in your partner now, your body won’t be able to surrender, either to true pleasure and intimacy, or to procreation.

trauma hurts us and the body always remembers, sometimes even when we do not.

as they say, the issues are in our tissue!

cellular memory of pain, fear or trauma, whether from this lifetime or your grandmother’s, can freeze your energy, inhibiting intimacy and sometimes even fertility!

our bodies want to protect us! 
healing these things requires the kind of gentleness, compassion, awareness and presence that were perhaps missing in the first place.

it helps so much to have a skillful nonjudgmental guide and ongoing sacred support.

this is why the luminous womb exists.

we help women worldwide bring love back to their libidos and unravel and thaw anything internal that may be hindering fertility or connection.

we’ve got you.
all of you is welcome here. 
video chat consults are always free! 
say hi anytime!

text:
me too post

this week! ugh this week is the week i dread and have started to fear every month. am i’m going to get hit with a migraine? how bad will it be? how many days will it last? will i have to call someone to take my boys to school? who am i inconveniencing today? how many days will i be in bed. how much pain will come this time? what plans to i have to cancel? these are the thoughts that go through my head every month right before this week hits! 
this is me last month on day 3 in bed with a migraine. this is the side that many of you don’t know or don’t have to see. this is a girl waiting for her healing, believing with all the faith in the world that it will come! i don’t post this so you can feel sorry for me, i post this because i want others to know they are not alone! for others who suffer like i do, for moms who miss their kids games because the pain is to much to bare or for those who wish people understood it’s so much worse then a headache. i’ve been on the search for years now for something that would take the pain away. i’m still searching and trying a more natural approach because i just don’t want to be on a prescription medication for the rest of my life! for those of you who suffer from migraines too please post below with a me too. i want to be praying for you daily as i know others pray for me. remember you’re not alone! #migrainesuck #myhealingiscoming #metoo @echosummerhill #motherofboys #motherofachildwithadhd

text:
“semper fi marine!” i can still hear my uncles voice- he was proud- he loved his country and he was one of the best people i knew. 
addiction stole his life this past year- but i’ll forever remember my uncle sober- that was how i knew him- he was one of my biggest supporters- challenged me to live my best life and to break the chains i allowed to hold me down for so long - he was one of the most loving people i’ve ever known- taught me the importance of “ starting my day over at any point” his memory will always remain- happy birthday marines!

text:
when will the sikh community have their own #metoo movement?
🔽
kaur siblings work together to prevent sexual violence and support survivors
🔽
while the movement’s push into the mainstream in late 2017 has led to it becoming an international front working to protect and help survivors around the world, the sikh research institute is wondering when the sikh community will have its own #metoo movement.
🔽
hoping to address this problem, the research institute—or sikhri for short—held an online webinar to discuss the matter at hand. sikhri aims to strengthen bonds within the sikh community, as well as make sikh education more accessible, through courses and seminars.
🔽
the webinar was led by gurleen kaur, an education and prevention specialist with the violence, prevention, and response team at mit, and jasleen kaur, a researcher at sikhri. the two have been working on an article set to be released by sikhri soon, as a culminating report of their research.

text:
frances discovered dream, girl the way many of our hosts come to the film - she attended a screening in miami. a few months before her event, she was seeking inspiration and with some encouragement from her husband, she decided to attend ani mercedes’ screening by herself. without knowing a single person in the room, frances remembers sitting alone in the theatre, eager to connect with the women in the room. 
but what happened after the screening was something she didn’t expect.
“i was shy and timid all by myself but as i was watching the documentary, just so many things spoke to me and i got my a-ha moment,” frances said. “it empowered me and moved me to pursue my jewelry line and try different things that i’ve always wanted to do." #womeninfilm #startupstory #startupcommunity #girlbossmagic #girlbossquotes #feministquotes #feministmovement #feministartist #femalefilmmaker #femalefilmmakers #femalefilmmakerfriday #ceos #ceomom #meditatedaily  #dreamerswelcome #dreamersunite #dreamerforever #metoo #timesup #supersoul #supersoulconversations #supersoul100 #dreamgirlfilm

text:
if you've never been raised in dysfunction, then you probably don't understand what i mean. chances are you believe poverty can be fixed by "simply going to college." you think single mothers who need assistance wouldn't be in their position if they would have just "stay of their backs or "you shouldn't have been so sexy." as if you are oblivious to the fact that there are sexual predators out here praying on women, men and children. that women or men shouldn't have a hard time coming forward to tell someone they were raped or sexually assaulted. as if these individuals aren't suffering from trauma. 
i can go on and on, but i  can see how you can think that way especially if you're never experience what it's like to grow up in poverty, where family members sexually and verbally abuse each other, where they have one or no parents usually raised by a grandparent. to look up at your elders for leadership and the answers only for them to have nothing if value to share with you other than "go to school and listen to them white folks".. what i'm saying is life is not just black and white, thus all the movement from people in the "grey" that have been at economic disadvantage and doing the best they can do to break the generational curse. 
i will elaborate more in future live youtube videos so please subscribe. thank you
